  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Heart of India</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Madhya Pradesh — the Middle Province — sits at the geographic, ecological and civilizational center of the Indian subcontinent. The largest state in India by area (308,252 sq km), it holds three UNESCO World Heritage Sites in extraordinary proximity: the erotic temples of Khajuraho built by the Chandela dynasty, the Buddhist monuments of Sanchi where Emperor Ashoka's Great Stupa has stood for 2,300 years, and the rock shelters of Bhimbetka containing paintings 30,000 years old — some of humanity's earliest art. MP is India's tiger capital — home to six of India's finest tiger reserves: Kanha, Bandhavgarh, Pench, Satpura, Panna and Tadoba. The Kanha meadows inspired Rudyard Kipling's Jungle Book — Mowgli's forest is real, still wild, still breathing. The sacred city of Ujjain holds one of the twelve Jyotirlingas and hosts the Kumbh Mela (Simhastha) every 12 years. Orchha's Bundela palaces rise from the Betwa river like a mirage of the 17th century, completely intact. Gwalior Fort — one of India's great citadels — surveys the Chambal plains from its crag. Mandu's deserted Sultanate city tells the legendary love story of Baz Bahadur and Roopmati in stone. The Narmada — one of India's most sacred rivers — rises at Amarkantak and flows west through marble gorges. Madhya Pradesh is India in its most elemental state — the forest, the stone, the river and the tiger, all still here.</p>
</section>
