const placesData=[
{emoji:"🛕",name:"Khajuraho Temple Complex",location:"Chhatarpur District",desc:"UNESCO World Heritage Site — 25 surviving temples of the 85 built by the Chandela dynasty between 950-1050 AD. The Kandariya Mahadeva temple rises 30 meters in a cascade of sandstone sculpture depicting every aspect of human and divine existence. The celebrated erotic carvings (about 10% of total) represent Tantric philosophy — the union of the earthly and divine. One of humanity's great architectural achievements.",fee:["Rs.40 Indians","Rs.600 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🏛️",name:"Sanchi Buddhist Monuments",location:"Raisen District",desc:"UNESCO World Heritage Site — Emperor Ashoka's Great Stupa, built in the 3rd century BC to enshrine the Buddha's relics. The four elaborately carved gateways (toranas) with scenes from the Buddha's life are among the finest examples of early Indian art. This hill of pilgrimage 46 km from Bhopal has remained undisturbed for 2,300 years — one of the most spiritually peaceful places in India.",fee:["Rs.30 Indians","Rs.500 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🦴",name:"Bhimbetka Rock Shelters",location:"Raisen District",desc:"UNESCO World Heritage Site — 750 rock shelters in the Vindhya foothills with paintings spanning 30,000 years of continuous human habitation. The oldest works are among humanity's earliest art. Ochre, white and green figures depict hunting, dancing and ritual. The extraordinary continuity — the same site used from the Paleolithic through medieval times — makes Bhimbetka one of archaeology's most remarkable places.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.250 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🐯",name:"Kanha Tiger Reserve",location:"Mandla-Balaghat",desc:"The forest that inspired Rudyard Kipling's Jungle Book — the Kanha meadows (maidans) are among the most beautiful wildlife landscapes in Asia. Home to Bengal tigers, the hard-ground barasingha (found nowhere else on earth), leopards, wild dogs and gaur. The morning safari through golden grassland at dawn, following a tiger's pug marks, is India's most iconic wildlife experience.",fee:["Zone-wise charges"]},
{emoji:"🐅",name:"Bandhavgarh Tiger Reserve",location:"Umaria District",desc:"India's highest density of Bengal tigers — the origin of virtually every white tiger in captivity worldwide (all descend from Mohan, caught here in 1951). The ancient Bandhavgarh Fort perched on an 800-meter rock with a 2,000-year-old reclining Vishnu carved into the cliff adds mythological gravity. Safaris here offer the best statistical chance of tiger sightings in India.",fee:["Zone-wise charges"]},
{emoji:"🏰",name:"Orchha Fort and Palace Complex",location:"Niwari District",desc:"A 17th-century Bundela capital rising from the Betwa river — seemingly unchanged since the Mughal era. The Jehangir Mahal (seven-story palace built to receive Emperor Jahangir), the Ram Raja Temple where Ram is worshipped as a king with military honors, and cenotaphs lining the river create a complete medieval city. The mist off the Betwa at dawn is breathtaking.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.250 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"⛩️",name:"Mahakaleshwar Temple, Ujjain",location:"Ujjain",desc:"One of the twelve Jyotirlingas — the Mahakaleshwar is one of Hinduism's most powerful sites. The Bhasma Aarti performed at 4am using cremation ashes is a ritual of raw intensity found nowhere else. Ujjain is one of seven sacred Hindu cities and hosts the Simhastha Kumbh Mela every 12 years. The Ram Ghat at dawn, with 100 temples along the Shipra river, is extraordinary.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Bhedaghat Marble Rocks",location:"Jabalpur",desc:"The Narmada cuts through 3 km of gleaming white marble cliffs — 30-meter walls of polished stone glowing rose-gold at sunset, reflected in the green water. The Dhuandhar waterfall thunders between the rocks downstream. Boat rides through the gorge by full moonlight — when the white marble shines silver — are legendary experiences that have drawn visitors since the colonial era.",fee:["Boat charges apply"]},
{emoji:"🦋",name:"Mandu — Hilltop Ghost City",location:"Dhar District",desc:"A deserted Sultanate capital on a 20-km plateau — Jahaz Mahal (Ship Palace), Hindola Mahal and Roopmati's Pavilion tell the legendary love story of Sultan Baz Bahadur and the singer Roopmati, who killed herself rather than surrender to Akbar's forces. Twelve sq km of medieval Islamic architecture in romantic ruin, surrounded by gorges and forest. The most beautiful ghost city in India.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.250 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🏔️",name:"Pachmarhi Hill Station",location:"Narmadapuram District",desc:"The only hill station in MP — a plateau at 1,067 meters in the Satpura ranges, surrounded by the Satpura Tiger Reserve. Dhupgarh at 1,352m (highest point in MP) gives views across the plateau at sunrise. Bee Falls, Jata Shankar cave, Pandava Caves and ancient rock paintings create a landscape of exceptional natural and archaeological richness.",fee:["Entry charges"]},
{emoji:"🦁",name:"Kuno National Park — Cheetah",location:"Sheopur District",desc:"The site of India's historic cheetah reintroduction project — African cheetahs were brought here in 2022 after the species was extinct in India for 70 years. The park's open grasslands, thorn forests and the Kuno river create an ecosystem being carefully restored. A wildlife destination of global conservation significance, still developing but already drawing wildlife enthusiasts worldwide.",fee:["Charges apply"]}
];

const artsData=[
{emoji:"🎨",name:"Gond Tribal Painting",location:"Mandla, Dindori, Balaghat",desc:"One of India's most internationally celebrated folk art forms — the Gond community paints intricate dot-and-dash patterns filling images of animals, trees and deities with vibrating visual energy. Jangarh Singh Shyam, discovered in the 1980s, was exhibited at the Pompidou Centre. Today Gond art is collected and exhibited globally as a major contemporary folk tradition."},
{emoji:"🧵",name:"Chanderi and Maheshwari Silk",location:"Chanderi (Ashoknagar) and Maheshwar",desc:"Two of India's finest handloom traditions. Chanderi — a gossamer-thin silk-cotton fabric woven since the 10th century with zari borders and traditional butis; GI-tagged. Maheshwari — created under Ahilyabai Holkar's patronage in the 18th century, distinguished by its reversible border. Both are woven in homes along the river by communities with a thousand-year loom knowledge."},
{emoji:"🪆",name:"Bagh Print and Natural Dye Craft",location:"Bagh Village, Dhar District",desc:"Natural dye block printing from Bagh on the Baghini river — geometric and floral patterns hand-printed with madder, indigo and turmeric. The Khatri family has practiced this for 15 generations. GI-tagged and internationally exhibited as one of India's finest textile traditions, Bagh print is now collected by design museums worldwide."},
{emoji:"🎭",name:"Malwa Maach Theatre",location:"Ujjain, Indore, Malwa Region",desc:"The traditional folk opera of the Malwa plateau — performed through the night with elaborate costumes, improvised dialogue and songs in the Malwi dialect. Maach deals with mythology, social satire and historical legends. The actor-singers are revered in their communities. Over 400 years old, Maach is still performed regularly at village festivals across Malwa."},
{emoji:"🥁",name:"Tertali Dance and Tribal Arts",location:"Rewa, Panna — Kamar Community",desc:"Tertali — a virtuoso seated dance performed by Kamar women of Baghelkhand with up to 13 manjira (cymbals) attached to different parts of their bodies. The complexity of coordinated rhythm is staggering. Combined with the Bhil Ghoomar of western MP and the Gondi ritual dances of the south, MP's tribal performing traditions are among the richest in India."},
{emoji:"🔔",name:"Gwalior Gharana and Classical Music",location:"Gwalior",desc:"Gwalior is the cradle of Hindustani classical music — the Gwalior Gharana is the oldest and most foundational school of North Indian classical vocal music, established under the patronage of the Tomar and Scindia dynasties. Tansen — one of the Navaratnas of Akbar's court — was trained here. Every major Hindustani vocalist traces lineage back to the Gwalior Gharana."}
