const traditionsData=[
{emoji:"💃",name:"Khajuraho Dance Festival",location:"Khajuraho — February",desc:"India's premier classical dance festival — held against the illuminated backdrop of the Khajuraho temples in the open air. Bharatanatyam, Kathak, Odissi, Manipuri, Kuchipudi and other classical forms are performed on stages built facing the Western Temple Group. The combination of India's finest dancers with India's finest medieval stone is one of the most beautiful experiences the country offers."},
{emoji:"🌸",name:"Bhagoria Haat — Bhil Tribal Festival",location:"Jhabua and Alirajpur — March",desc:"The extraordinary pre-Holi festival of the Bhil tribe — village fairs where young men and women meet, court and elope with chosen partners. If a girl accepts the gulal thrown by a young man, she agrees to marry him. Bhagoria is one of India's few surviving community courtship festivals — joyful, colorful and deeply rooted in tribal freedom and social consent."},
{emoji:"🔱",name:"Simhastha Kumbh Mela",location:"Ujjain — Every 12 Years",desc:"Ujjain's Kumbh Mela when Jupiter enters Leo — sadhus of all akharas gather on the Shipra banks. Millions bathe on auspicious dates. The processions of Naga sadhus — ash-covered, carrying tridents, riding elephants and horses — are among the most spectacular religious processions in the world. The next Simhastha is in 2028."},
{emoji:"🏰",name:"Orchha Ram Navami",location:"Orchha — March/April",desc:"Ram Navami at Orchha is spectacular — the Ram Raja Temple (where Rama is worshipped as a king with state honors) marks the occasion with cannon salutes, a military guard of honor and processions. The only place in India where Lord Ram receives a full military salute daily. The confluence of royalty, devotion and architecture makes this one of MP's most distinctive festivals."},
{emoji:"🎵",name:"Tansen Music Festival",location:"Gwalior — November/December",desc:"India's premier classical Hindustani music festival held at Tansen's tomb in Gwalior. Four days of the finest classical vocalists and instrumentalists performing at the Hazira tomb complex. The legend that singing under Tansen's tamarind tree improves one's voice draws musicians from across India. The most important annual event in North Indian classical music."},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Narmada Jayanti and Parikrama",location:"Amarkantak and Narmada Banks",desc:"The Narmada is worshipped as a goddess and circumambulated (parikrama) as the only river in India walked as a pilgrimage — a 2,600 km circuit along both banks taking 3 years. Narmada Jayanti celebrates the river's birth at Amarkantak. The dawn bathing at Amarkantak where the Narmada and Son rivers emerge from the same plateau is one of MP's most spiritually potent experiences."}
];

const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🌾",name:"Dal Bafla",region:"Malwa — State Signature Dish",desc:"The soul food of MP — wheat dough balls boiled then baked until golden, cracked open and drowned in ghee, served with thick dal and a ladoo. The Rajasthani baati's richer MP cousin. Eaten at every dhaba from Bhopal to Indore as the definitive comfort food of the Malwa plateau. The combination of textures — crisp outside, soft inside, bathed in clarified butter — is immensely satisfying."},
{emoji:"🌽",name:"Bhutte Ka Kees",region:"Indore — Malwa Street Specialty",desc:"Fresh corn grated and cooked in ghee with green chilies, coriander, mustard seeds and lime until fluffy and aromatic. Served from roadside carts in earthen bowls. A dish impossible to eat without smiling. The Indori street food scene — bhutte ka kees, poha, jalebi, garadu — is considered one of India's finest urban street food cultures."},
{emoji:"🫓",name:"Indori Poha",region:"Indore",desc:"The definitive MP breakfast — flattened rice cooked with onion, mustard seeds, curry leaves and turmeric, topped with sev, pomegranate seeds, fresh coriander and lime. Served with jalebi for dipping. Indore's poha is nationally considered the finest version — lighter, more fragrant and more complexly garnished than anywhere else in India. A breakfast that defines a city."},
{emoji:"🍬",name:"Mawa Bati and Morena Gajak",region:"Gwalior, Morena",desc:"Mawa Bati — a golden fried pastry ball stuffed with mawa, dry fruits and saffron, dipped in syrup — is MP's most beloved sweet. Morena's Gajak (GI-tagged sesame brittle with jaggery) is made from white sesame grown on the Chambal plateau and is the finest in India. Gajak is Gwalior's most famous winter export — sent across the country from October to February."},
{emoji:"🌶️",name:"Ratlami Sev",region:"Ratlam — GI Tagged National Icon",desc:"India's most distinctive sev — a chickpea flour noodle preparation with cloves, black pepper and carom seeds giving it a fiery, spiced complexity impossible to replicate elsewhere. GI-tagged, Ratlami sev is the definitive MP snack, exported across India. The town of Ratlam has been making this sev for 400 years and it appears on restaurant menus across India as a garnish."},
{emoji:"🥘",name:"Bhopali Non-Vegetarian Cuisine",region:"Bhopal — Nawabi Heritage",desc:"Bhopal's Muslim ruling legacy left extraordinary culinary depth — keema samosa, bhopali gosht korma, rogan josh, nihari and the Bhopali paan. The old city's haleem, biryani and kebab culture near Jama Masjid reflects centuries of Nawabi patronage. Bhopal's kebab tradition — with its use of whole spices and slow cooking — rivals Lucknow in subtlety and depth of flavor."},
{emoji:"🍖",name:"Poha-Jalebi and Sabudana Khichdi",region:"Malwa — Fasting and Festival Food",desc:"The beloved MP pairing of savory poha with sweet crispy jalebis for breakfast — a counterintuitive combination of extraordinary pleasure. Sabudana khichdi — sago pearls with peanuts, ghee and green chili — is the universal fasting food. The tribal communities of MP's forests add extraordinary variety: mahua preparations, bamboo shoot dishes and wild honey from the Vindhya forests."},
{emoji:"🫕",name:"Chakki Ki Shaak",region:"Bundelkhand Region",desc:"Whole-wheat dough cooked in a spiced curry sauce — a unique Bundelkhand dish of extreme frugality transformed into comfort food. The dough absorbs the curry's flavors from within. A food born from necessity that has become a regional identity dish. Eaten with lentils and flatbread across the Bundelkhand plateau, it sustains communities through the region's notoriously hot and dry summers."},
